It’s a money making scheme for the energy suppliers..
Charge over night when wholesale energy is ≈4p  and release it at peak when they are currently ≈60 per kw.
Octopus charge going rate for electricity on their loop tariff and you get £30 per month to degrade the battery

If the reserve of energy was controlled by the vehicle owner they could choose when to sell back to the grid.

Example - octopus agile charged 10p to charge over night but were buying it back at peak for £1.30 based on a few days in January.

Even based on today it’s 5p to charge overnight and 24p to discharge.≈£7.60 

For a 40kw car battery you could make £90 for those days. Those on the loop tarriff were making £1.

As technology evolves ultra fast charging of solid state batteries will demand a more locally distributed power network. Car parks will turn into energy storage facilities. Lifecycle concerns will be removed. FI03_01: Generally, technology is not yet evolved enough. Whilst LTO and NTO give sufficient life-cycles to support V2G their energy density is too low for most vehicle applications. FI02_01: At present, I have a PodPoint tethered charger on my wall with a charge time set for 01.00 - 05.00 every day, meaning that all that I need to do is plug in my cable and charging will take place. With the V2G option, I do not see currently (a definite pun intended here!) much extra benefit to me unless these were either financial (bill reduction or the like) or the option to charge at any time of day for any period of time rather than leaving things to run overnight. I do like the idea of being able to use my car to power my house in the case of major electrical failures, even with only a 24 kWh battery like mine. If there were an incentive with regards cost of charging, then this would have to equal or better any existing EV tarrif/s, in which case my interest would be increased.
FI03_01: As noted above, bar the reversing of current flow from car to network / house then the benefits are not altogether clear and obvious since many electricity providers do have specific EV tarrifs so there would need to be a significant incentive or benefit to be gained from swapping to this system. Secondly, if swapping required the purchase and installation of a new charging point then probably I would not go ahead, even with a substantial grant, knowing the cost of having my PodPoint installed with the full 500 pound at the time. I doubt that the outlay and savings in the short term would recoup any cost on my part.

If I was going to the local supermarket I could plug into their V2G chargers and have free electrical charge up while I am shopping. I usually take 60 mins which would cover my trip there and back and still leave me with a plus charge in my battery. 
There are several V2G points in my area where I could charge up and if I was going into town on the tram then I could plug in and leave it there to charge while I am away. However unlike the supermarket charges these cost to recharge and you are only allowed to plug in for a certain time. However I have noticed that there are many more plug in stations by the tram/station stop than cars so at the moment noone is monitoring these to see how long you stay. That could change in the future.
If I was going on a long journey then I would have to see the map which showed the locations of charges as the range of charge in my battery would not be enough to get me back home. However the chargers are available in a lot of petrol stations and outside coffee shops so should not be a problem.

On a national level the stabilisation of the electric grid to allow the country to store electricity loically at periods of low demand and release it at periods of high demands would help us to reduce the burning of fossil fuels by enabling us to take unused wind power at times of low demand. Wind produces power whilst the blades are turning regardless of whether the country needs it. Without massive battery storage this is generally lost. At some point it must be hoped we can produce hydrogen with this 'wasted' energy and therby allow us to store a fuel for use in periods of high demand. In the meantime millions of batteries can take up that slack and hold it locally across the entire grid.
A secondary attraction is the ability to earn revenue, either by selling electricity back to the grid or using cheaper acquired electricity from out of hours charging in your home.
